default4.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRecommendations default4.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultActive promotion of cycling:default While we are sure many submis
defaultsions to the select committee will highlight the need to redesign the road environment helping to reduce the risk and the perception of risk, we believe cheaper immediate wins could be achieved by positive marketing of cycling as desirable low risk benign 
defaultactivity that anyone can do.
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultCreate a road sharing environment:default Bikeability and National Standard cycle training gives people on bikes the skills to share the road with people in motor vehicles by communicating to them through looking and road positioning
default. Ensuring that the speed differential between modes is low would encourage riders to move within the flow of traffic and discourage drivers from ‘punishing’ people on bikes using aggressive behaviour when the driver perceives the cyclists as ‘in their way
default’. 20mph (or lower) speed limits in all urban areas, enforced through design and policing would help people share the road space
default&#xa0;
default4.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultFunding and promotion of adult cycle trainingdefault: rebranding it to remove the child-centred stigma attached (Urban riding skills 
defaulttraining perhaps?) would help adults make the transition from off road leisure riders to everyday cyclists in a short time. T
default&#xa0;
default4.4
default&#xa0; 
defaultContinued funding and promotion of Bikeability for young people:default through the Bikeability schemes and Youth Sports Trusts. Such fu
defaultnding should be guaranteed across terms of government. Up-skilling people of all ages through training as well as messages about how to road share will minimise risk on the roads
default&#xa0;
default4.5
default&#xa0; 
defaultFunding and promotion of on-bike driver trainingdefault: While this has been happen
defaulting for too short a time to accrue more than anecdotal evidence of the value of getting drivers on bikes there is definitely a case from the small amount of feedback received from participants (TfL have this data) to recommend that this scheme be scaled up
default nationally and that anyone who drives a lorry or a bus on roads where people ride bikes should get such training. The training should also be rolled-out to all professional drivers.
default&#xa0;
default4.6
default&#xa0; 
defaultCycle training for anyone who a gets a driving licencedefault: If, as a society
default we seriously wish to normalise cycling and minimise road risk, demonstrating the ability to ride on road and understand the basics of the highway code should be demonstrated on a bicycle before people are allowed a provisional driving licence.
